Posted: Sun May 06, 2012 6:11 am
Quote:Concussions are a matter of degree often. And light concussions happen to people quite often and they don't even realize it. The brain has a remarkable ability to repair itself.Where do you come up with this stuff? Do you understand anything about how head trauma works? The brain does not have a remarkable ability to repair itself. The brain, much like the rest of your CNS, is fragile. Once something breaks, the body may be able to stop further damage (may!), but the damage done is already done. This is why ALS, MS, CTE, Alzheimer's, and Parkinson's diseases are so debilitating. The worst part is, is that the very small amount of damage that causes some these diseases is almost never noticeable when it occurs. The damage is ongoing and cumulative, however, and 10, 20, 30 or more years later reaches a critical mass where the symptoms are very visible. Nothing can be done at that point except slow the disease progression and treat the symptoms. These are progressive CNS diseases that the body can NOT recover from.For an example, read articles 1-34 at this link or any of the 153 articles here for a better understanding of brain trauma and progressive neurodegenerative diseases. There is still a lot more research to be done to determine exact causes and hopefully some clinical research into repairing the damage, but we certainly have a wealth of scientific knowledge on head trauma that you should read about instead of spouting your non-scientific and incorrect beliefs. You are demonstrably wrong and until you take the time to educate yourself fully, you should not be repeating your non-scientific nonsense where anyone who might incorrectly make a decision based on it.Don't mistake me for saying that playing football will inevitably lead to any of these diseases. There is only weak correlation at this point, no causation. These guys who have committed suicide and whose brains show signs of neurological damage could have been exposed to a chemical that caused it, bumped their head going down the stairs or in the shower, by crushing beer cans on their forehead, or some combination. Who knows? I am only pointing out that the brain does not have a magical ability to repair itself from head trauma, regardless of the cause.
