Posted: Mon May 07, 2012 12:10 am
ronelson wrote:Don't mistake me for saying that playing football will inevitably lead to any of these diseases. There is only weak correlation at this point, no causation. These guys who have committed suicide and whose brains show signs of neurological damage could have been exposed to a chemical that caused it, bumped their head going down the stairs or in the shower, by crushing beer cans on their forehead, or some combination. Who knows? I am only pointing out that the brain does not have a magical ability to repair itself from head trauma, regardless of the cause.That's true in a literal sense, of course. However, the brain is capable of "rerouting" itself in many cases, such that in effect an injury to one part of it can be entirely mitigated by making use of resources elsewhere, much like a traffic system can continue to function perfectly well if a sinkhole develops on a side street. At least, that's the way my neurologist explained the general function to me; my condition, unfortunately, is akin to that sinkhole appearing on a major freeway with no other roads around, which is why I'll always have symptoms.Anyway, the point is it's not that unreasonable nor unrealistic to say that the brain "has a remarkable ability to repair itself". It does, it's just that it can only do so up to a point and as more and more evidence comes in, it's looking like football, like some other sports, has a tendency to take players' brains well beyond that point.
ronelson
Ars Legatus Legionis
Tribus: Richmond, VA
Registered: Mar 21, 1999Posts: 21393
Posted: Mon May 07, 2012 5:57 am
Quote:However, the brain is capable of "rerouting" itself in many casesBut that is not repair. Your CNS is using previously unused but intact pathways. If those pathways are then damaged, it will have to find another unused pathway. When you run out, you run out.Quote:such that in effect an injury to one part of it can be entirely mitigated by making use of resources elsewhereNot exactly true. Even though your CNS may be using some other pathway, the damage itself has not gone away. Inflammation in particular is progressive. Without getting into it too much (read some of the research I linked to), inflammation can cause some cells in the brain to become too aggressive and start attacking other brain cells, and then those cells start doing the same thing. This is why these things get worse over time after the trauma is gone. It is just not visible until too late, when the brain starts to run out of alternative pathways to use or memory is destroyed, or both. The damage has been worked around, but not mitigated.Quote:Anyway, the point is it's not that unreasonable nor unrealistic to say that the brain "has a remarkable ability to repair itself". It doesAgain, it has nothing of the sort, and insisting that it does in the face of scientific evidence to the contrary is not helping anyone.I am sorry to hear that you have transverse myelitis. I hope you have a full recovery.
