Posted: Mon May 07, 2012 8:04 am
ronelson wrote:Quote:Concussions are a matter of degree often. And light concussions happen to people quite often and they don't even realize it. The brain has a remarkable ability to repair itself.Where do you come up with this stuff? Do you understand anything about how head trauma works? I don't know, a part of my degree is in Computational Neuroscience, but I'm sure with your authoritative and didactic tone, you think you know more than me. I actually studied the subject, did computational modeling work with various neural subsystems, and performed research in several Neurophysiology and Neuroanatomy labs.For instance, the brain suffers light trauma every time you sneeze...you can effectively get a "concussion" if you sneeze hard enough. So everyday bumps, falls, accidents etc and other types of trauma can have similar effects. In those cases, the person never realizes what has happened. Brain cell death is a common occurrence, and "rerouting" of signaling pathwsys very commonplace. This is a form of "repair", but it's a repair of function, not form.I have a co-worker who is missing almost half of his left frontal lobe (tumor). You'd never know if you met him.Severe concussions have different pathologies (and they are quite rare...even in football). Here you have a hard enough inertial impact that causes the brain to actually bruise itself on the skull's interior. This is severe trauma...which still can be "repaired". But there's obviously a limit to how many of those severe impacts your brain can take.
