ronelson wrote:Quote:However, the brain is capable of "rerouting" itself in many casesBut that is not repair. Your CNS is using previously unused but intact pathways. If those pathways are then damaged, it will have to find another unused pathway. When you run out, you run out.Yes, I know. That's why I said that you were right "in a literal sense". I'm just pointing out that it can compensate for damage up to a point such that it's a kind of de facto "repair" from the perspective of the person involved. Obviously, in the case of some brain injuries that doesn't happen and, worse, some injuries are so severe (and/or cumulative) that they prompt degenerative conditions, as you mentioned.Quote:I am sorry to hear that you have transverse myelitis. I hope you have a full recovery.Like I said, I never will. But so far the recurrent symptoms I have had have been very minor. As long as I don't go hiking in very hot places it's no big deal, basically.---kray28 wrote:Brain cell death is a common occurrence, and "rerouting" of signaling pathwsys very commonplace. This is a form of "repair", but it's a repair of function, not form.Yes, that's what I was trying to get at, but you put it much clearer than I did!
